Here is how you can convert the Python code snippet `x='x,2,3,4'.replace(',', '')` into C:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
    // create a string with commas
    char x[] = "x,2,3,4";

    // replace commas with empty string
    for (int i = 0; i < strlen(x); i++) {
        if (x[i] == ',') {
            memmove(&x[i], &x[i + 1], strlen(x) - i);
            i--;
        }
    }

    printf("%s\n", x);

    return 0;
}
```

This C code first creates a character array `x` with the string "x,2,3,4". It then loops through each character in the array using a `for` loop and checks if the current character is a comma. If so, it uses the `memmove` function to shift all the characters to the right of the comma one position to the left, effectively removing the comma. The loop then backtracks one position to check the next character in case there are multiple commas in a row. Finally, the resulting string with no commas is printed to the console.
